login_session: To answer this question, two psychologists at Dartmouth College, William Norris and Robert Miller, conducted an experiment with two groups. Participants were asked to evaluate the number of dots in a panel similar to the one on the left. Participants always responded last in a group that included other four people. Unbeknown to the participant the other four people were confederates -- members of the research team who were aware of the manipulation, and provided pre-defined answers.

<material>Having a partner that deviates from the group response might allow

different response reduces the consensus among the group and consolidates
the participant’s a priori correct estimate. </material>

<material> It is possible that younger children are more likely to conform with

login_session: the group opinion for one of two reasons. One possibility is that younger
children do not understand the task as well as older children and therefore
are more likely to provide the answer they hear other children provide.
Another possibility is that younger children’s cognitive system is less
developed than their older counterparts. Because of that, they might have a
more error-prone understanding of the world and may be more easily swayed
even when their perception is correct. </material>

<material>The results of this study indicate that the mere presence of another

login_session: person is sufficient to influence an individual’s behavior. These results
were obtained with a trivial incidental task that was not easily amenable to
evaluation and the subject believed was only a preparation for the actual
experiment. These results suggest that the improvement in performance in the
presence of an audience is not the result of the feeling of being evaluated,
but a more generic arousal associated with the presence of a social stimulus

supplement: <material>The researchers concluded that the results of this study indicate that

login_session: domain-identification -- feeling that the domain is important to you --
plays a role on whether activating stereotypes has a detrimental effect on
performance or not. This is because, if we do not identify with the domain
of the stereotype, we are unlikely to activate stereotype implications
regarding our ability in the task. </material>

supplement: <material>The researchers concluded that by presenting the test as one on which

login_session: gender differences do not occur, they made the stereotype of women’s math
inability irrelevant to interpreting their performance on the test—this
particular test. It allowed these women to be as unconcerned with the
gender-based stereotype as equally qualified men, which, in turn, allowed
them to perform as well as these men. These findings provide strong evidence
that women’s underperformance on these difficult math tests results from
stereotype threat, rather than from sex-linked ability differences that are
detectable only on advanced math material.</material>

login_session: domain-identification -- feeling that the domain is important to you --

regarding our ability in the task. </material>

supplement: <material>The researchers concluded that by presenting the test as one on which

login_session: gender differences do not occur, they made the stereotype of women’s math
inability irrelevant to interpreting their performance on the test—this
particular test. It allowed these women to be as unconcerned with the
gender-based stereotype as equally qualified men, which, in turn, allowed
them to perform as well as these men. These findings provide strong evidence
that women’s underperformance on these difficult math tests results from
stereotype threat, rather than from sex-linked ability differences that are
detectable only on advanced math material.</material>

al describes the process whereby people make a mistake in assuming what is causing them to feel aroused. For example, when actually experiencing physiological responses related to fear, people mislabel those responses as romantic arousal. Does the valence of the arousal affect the direction of the misattribution effect?

login_session: To answer this question, a group of psychologists at the University of Maryland, University of Notre Dame, and Rutgers University conducted an experiment. In this study, the researchers tested whether arousal with both positive and negative valence increased attractiveness ratings of an actor compared to a low arousal condition. Male participants were divided into one of 3 groups. Participants in one of the groups started by listening to a taped testimony of a grisly murder (Negative Arousal Condition). Participants in another group started by listening to a taped recording of a comedy show (Positive Arousal Condition). The last group listened to a description of the frog’s circulatory system (Neutral Arousal Condition). Following this, all participants watched a video of a female actor in which the actor wore form-fitting attractive clothes, had her face and hair made up attractively, and delivered the script in an energetic way. After watching the video all participants filled a questionnaire rating the actor’s attractiveness. The measure of interest is the attractiveness rating in this questionnaire.

supplement: As shown by Asch’s classic studies, people often conform to the majority opinion of a group.  Does conformity to group responses change with age?

login_session: To answer this question, two psychologists, Michael Walker and Maria Andrade, conducted an experiment with children. Children in this study were divided into 4 groups based on their age. A 3-5 age group, a 6-8 age group, a 9-11 age group, and a 12-14 age group. Participants were asked to identify which one of three lines matched in length the reference line provided (see figure on the right). Participants always responded last in a group that included three confederates (classmates of the same age who were instructed to provide a clearly wrong answer before the start of the experiment without the participant’s knowledge). All confederates provided the incorrect response. Researchers measured how many times participants provided an incorrect response out of all responses provided (i.e., percent conformity).
